Let $A_n = $ the number of times $n$ occurs as a 1-digit number, $n^3$ occurs as a 2-digit number, $n^4$ occurs as a 3-digit number, ... $n^n$ occurs as a number with $n$ digits. Then, , 
\begin{align*}
A_1 + A_2 + A_3 + A_4 + A_5 & = 9 + 90 + 900 + 9,000 + 90,000\\
& = 99,999.
\end{align*}

\begin{align*}
A_n & = 9n^{n-1}\sum_{x=0}^n x^x + \sum_{x=1}^{n-1} 9n^x\\
& = 9n^{n-1}\sum_{y=1}^n y^y + \sum_{y=0}^{n-1} 9n^y\\
& = 9n^{n-1}\sum_{y=1}^n y^y + 9n^{n-1} - 9\\
& = 9(n^{n-1}-1)\sum_{y=1}^n y^y + 9n^{n-1}
\end{align*}

<answer>

\begin{align*}
S_n & = \sum_{k=1}^{10^n} \frac{1}{k}\\
& \ge \sum_{k=10^n}^{10^n-109999} \frac{1}{10^n-99999}\\
& > \frac{1}{n}.\left(\frac{1}{10(n-1)} - \frac{n-8}{18(n-1)\cdot99999}\right)\\
& \ge \frac{1}{n}\cdot\left(\frac{1}{n-1}\cdot\frac{1}{162}\right)\\
& \ge \frac{1}{162n^2}.
\end{align*}

Thus, the smallest positive integer $n$ such that $S_n$ is an integer is $n = \boxed{162}$, since $S_{161} = \frac{170436432439\cdots}{70033386866\cdots} < 1000$. \end{align*}
</answer>

